Usually, warfarin is avoided in the first trimester , and a low-molecular-weight heparin such as enoxaparin is substituted. With heparin, risks of maternal haemorrhage and other complications are still increased, but heparins do not cross the placental barrier, so do not cause birth defects. [ 42 ] Various solutions exist for the time around delivery.

